colnames(data) <- c("timestamp", "utc_offset",

So, letâs look at the distribution of data for the energy usage, that will give us an idea as to what our thesis should be:

hist(data$energy_usage)

So, what do we have to engineer features from? Well, the only real thing we have is the Timestamp variable. So, letâs use lubridate and engineer atomic variables. I will be using Hadleyâs dplyr for this. Since wday returns 7 for sunday and 1 for saturday, it kind of messes up some stuff, so Iâm going to go ahead and make 1 monday and 7 sunday.

data %>% mutate(tstamp=ymd_hms(timestamp)) %>%
  mutate(feat_hour=hour(tstamp),
         feat_month=month(tstamp),
         feat_day_of_week=wday(tstamp)) %>%
  mutate(feat_day_of_week=feat_day_of_week-1) %>%
  mutate(feat_day_of_week=ifelse(feat_day_of_week == 0, 7, feat_day_of_week)) %>%
          mutate(feat_weekend=feat_day_of_week %in% c(6, 7)) %>% 
  mutate(feat_hour=as.factor(feat_hour),
          feat_month=as.factor(feat_month),
          feat_day_of_week=as.factor(feat_day_of_week),
          feat_weekend=as.factor(feat_weekend)) -> data

So, what features did we extract:

  • feat_hour - the hour of the reading
  • feat_day_of_week - the day of the week
  • feat_month - the month of the reading
  • feat_weekend - a binary feature for whether things are a weekend or not

Ok, so now letâs visualize the data with some of these new features, for starters letâs look by hour of the day by day of week.

ggplot(data, aes(x=feat_hour, y=energy_usage)) + 
  geom_bar(stat="identity") + 
  facet_wrap(~ feat_day_of_week)

Pretty clear, this bank isnât open on Sundays or Saturdays (day 1 and 7). So, the feat_day_of_week feature is going to be silly predictive. We also created the âweekendâ feature, which is a BINARY feature, which are incredibly powerful predictively, letâs see what that graph looks like.

ggplot(data, aes(x=feat_hour, y=energy_usage)) + 
  geom_bar(stat="identity") + 
  facet_wrap(~ feat_weekend)

Yeah, there you go. Almost certainly feat_weekend is going to be part of this.

However, the curve weâre trying to predict is very much that, itâs a curve, so this isnât really a fit for a linear regression.

ggplot(data, aes(x=as.integer(as.character(feat_hour)), y=energy_usage)) + 
  geom_smooth() + 
  facet_wrap(~ feat_weekend)

The problem as you stated it is a bit tough:

Iâm trying to extract features from it and train a model on this sample data that predicts whether the bank of open or closed

Well, we donât have a target label for âis openâ or âis closedâ, so the first thing we can do is train a regressor instead of a classifier, and say, given the features weâve extracted, how good a job can we do in predicting the kWH that will be used?

Letâs bust out some caret, first we create a train/test split:

inTrain <- createDataPartition(data$energy_usage, p=.8, list=FALSE)
train <- data[inTrain,]
test <- data[-inTrain,]

Since weâre trying to do some regression, we donât have a lot of predictors. We could pick something more complicated, but life is short. Weâre trying to fit non-linear data, but letâs see how far a simple lm gets us.

lm.fit <- train(energy_usage ~ feat_hour + feat_weekend + feat_month,
                 data=train, method="lm")

An adjusted R-squared of 0.6552566 is not bad. 65% of variance is predictable just using the hour of the day, whether itâs a weekend, and what month it is!

Ok, so I guess the next question is, letâs engineer a label to âclassifyâ against, weâre going to make an is_open label. Weâre literally just going to make it by adding a column where if energy_usage > 60 kWh, itâs open.

data %>% mutate(is_open=as.factor(ifelse(energy_usage > 60, 
                                         TRUE, FALSE))) -> data

Ok, so letâs now train a simple classifer on the previous values on this new is_open categorical value. First we create the new train/test split.

inTrain <- createDataPartition(data$is_open, p=.8, list=FALSE)
train <- data[inTrain,]
test <- data[-inTrain,]

So how good are we at predicting whether itâs open (by which we mean more than 60 kWh used) using the hour, whether itâs a weekend, and the month?

glm.fit <- train(as.factor(is_open) ~ feat_hour + feat_weekend + feat_month, 
                 data=train, method="glm", trControl=trainControl(method="cv"))

Ok, our accuracy is 0.9362045! So, with the hour, the weekend, and the month, we can predict if weâre going to use <60 kWh with close to 94% accuracy on the training set. How do we do on the test set?

confusionMatrix(test$is_open, predict(glm.fit, test))
